The cocaine-addicted lawyer who warned the mobster about a police investigation is in jail
Basharat Ditta, 42, was supposed to pass information to the King of the Underworld, Neil Scarbrough.
The lawyer was afraid his drug addiction would come out.
Liverpool Crown Court sentenced him to three years in prison.
A top defense attorney who informed a drug mafia about a major police investigation, fearing his drug addiction would come out, was sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, was supposed to pass sensitive information to the underworld boss Neil Scarbrough about the investigation into his drug-smuggling activities after he became suspected of using cocaine.
The lawyer, nicknamed Bash (party) and hailed by criminals as the best lawyer, was arrested at his home in 2011 after police tracked down Scarborough, whom he had represented in previous narcotics cases.
Police spotted Sarborough, 32, leaving three bags of cocaine at the lawyer's house in Blackburn, Lancashire, where he was having dinner with his law firm colleagues.
Based on tests that found traces of cocaine in his hair, his wallet and his credit cards, the investigation revealed that Ditta was a regular user of Class A drugs.
During an eight-month period, from January to August 2011, he quietly sought information on the arrests of two men in favour of Scarborough and his accomplice.
All four suspects were being tracked at the time as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in the counties of Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
After police seized around £1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine during a series of raids, along with £200,000 in cash, 32 others ended up in prison with them.
Ditta, 42, passed information to criminals for fear of being exposed to cocaine addiction.
Today, Ditta, who works for Forbes Solicitors, a Blackburn-based law firm, experienced a shameful moment at Liverpool Crown Court when he was found guilty of obstructing justice in two cases after a three-week trial.
He admitted to possession of cocaine at an earlier hearing.
The lawyer's fall came after police investigation into Scarborough revealed that he had been in regular phone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two detectives tracked the suspect, recorded his arrival at Ditt's house, and spotted him placing a 60 percent purity drug under the lawyers' basket in a black golf glove.
Scarborough was then in regular telephone conversation with Ditta, who was having dinner at Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park.
The lawyer returned home, where he found the drugs, and there were nine conversations between the two men.
It was reported in court that traces of class A drugs were found in his hair, wallet and credit cards and that Ditta was a "regular cocaine user".
Ditta was later arrested, but denied using cocaine, and said he spoke to the suspected dealer because he was his client, arguing that their conversation fell within "confidential communication".
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to take out several credit cards, but they were all intercepted and his hair samples were taken.
During police interrogation, he said that he had an office at both his home and workplace addresses and that clients visited him at home for business.
But the court heard that after key arrests, he contacted major players in the drug supply chain, some of whom he had previously represented, to tell them what detectives knew about them.
The prosecutor, Anne Whyte, said: "No one knows better than a criminal lawyer that he must not break the law".
Mr. Ditta is charged with misuse of his position as counsel and getting too close to a particular client.
The relationship we're talking about here is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer who supplies his own lawyer with drugs.
Some of his conversations were undoubtedly legitimate, because he was his lawyer.
But it went way beyond the usual lawyer-client relationship.
He disrupted the police investigation as much as he could to allow them to continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta has not brought his profession good repute, but rather disgraced it.
He's gotten too close to some of his clients, especially Scarborough, and he's allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied the offence and stated: "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and I wanted to pass information to Mr Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, but I would do it immediately".
However, after the hearing, Lancashire Police Inspector Lee Halstead said: "Mr Ditta went from being a criminal lawyer to a criminal himself when he started procuring drugs from organised criminals".
His cocaine addiction left him hopelessly weak and vulnerable to the intentions of the top organized crime figures who tasked him with gathering valuable information for police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and must inspire confidence and a sense of trust in the public.
Mr. Ditta betrayed that trust and tried to hide behind the cloak of his profession.
The Lancashire Serious and Organised Crime Unit has conducted an investigation into Mr Ditt, which has also led to his conviction on three counts of possession of cocaine and now one count of obstruction of justice, demonstrating our commitment to bringing the perpetrators to justice.
This case should serve as a warning to all criminals that no one is beyond the reach of the law.
We will find you and bring you before our courts.
