A federal appeals court on Thursday blocked a court order requiring changes to the police department's arrest and search program and dismissed the judge's case.
The U.S. Second Circuit Court of Appeals said Judge Shira Scheindlin's decision will be stayed pending the city's decision on the appeal.
A judge ruled in August that the city violated the Constitution by implementing its program of stopping and interrogating people.
The city challenged its findings and its corrective regulations, including the decision to assign oversight to help the police department change its procedures and its related training program.
The appeals court heard arguments for the requested stay on Tuesday.
The Court of Appeal said that the judge must be dismissed from the case because she had come into conflict with the rules of conduct for judges by not acting as a judge as required to avoid appearances of sympathy, in part because of a series of media interviews and public statements in which she openly responded to the court's criticism.
The judge ruled that police officers violated the civil rights of tens of thousands of people by unfairly targeting blacks and Hispanics as part of their arrest and search program.
