In 2004, four men, all of whom are minorities, filed a lawsuit that became a class action lawsuit.
Proponents of changes to the NYPD's stop-and-search program argue that the changes will end unfair practices, increase the credibility and efficiency of the police force, and may affect how these practices are used by other police departments.
Opponents argue that the changes will reduce police morale but not crime, and that it will waste money, but will not solve the broader problem of the police force being under pressure after its numbers have shrunk by several thousand over the past decade.
