George Kerevan: Divided Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another scary story of independence.
This time, the warning appears that the condition for an independent Scotland's EU membership would be its entry into Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport controls in Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
It is true that the Strathclyde newspaper mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but  as might be expected  it did not make headlines.
Nor did anyone mention that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws when it suits them.
Given that Scotland is not now in Schengen, an offer of continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for whatever it really wants from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
The journalistic duck that "independence means passport control" I heard at least 40 years ago.
Yet, there is an interesting thought in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe?
Why trade the London chomout for the Brussels one, especially now?
This is the true story of Europe: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
The so-called Europe Project is officially dead because of the euro crisis.
Across Europe, parties dedicated to resisting the EU or abolishing the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party founded this year came out of nowhere and already won almost five million votes in the federal election in September, effectively ousting the Free Democrats (the British equivalent of the Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
At home, there has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, has become the turning point.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, together with the straitjacket imposed on national economies by sticking to the single currency, have led many to conclude that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments managing high budget deficits  this was true only in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a euro system that locks its members in exchange rates favourable to German exporters, and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing its domestic currency, southern Europe is at a disadvantage compared to Germany in terms of domestic production.
The only way to help is to cut public revenue and expenditure, which Germany is encouraging.
The current budgetary and monetary problems are rooted in the European poor performance.
As a result of the 'green' energy policy promoted by Brussels, the 'code' for supporting French and German companies at the expense of consumers, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gasoline as it does in the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
Even all the wage freezes in the world would not deter the European petrochemical industry from being flooded with cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a raging revolt, especially in France, once a staunch supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as an instrument to keep Germany in check and allow Paris to be on the same level as Washington in the world.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a proof of political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policies in Europe and left the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right wing, the anti-European National Front, just won a crucial by-election, pushing the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote  a timely warning to British Labour that they cannot assume that the split on the right will automatically translate into a positive left.
How is Le Pen handling her newfound popularity among the white working class?
She would like to use the European elections next year to create an anti-European bloc across the European Parliament, acting against the single currency.
If the anti-European parties do well in this election, which is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in history.
I think that in the near future, the growing anti-European sentiment and the attitude against the single currency will come together and the euro will be destroyed.
The EU will not disappear, but rather transform itself into something more free in the sense of the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favoured.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and join the United States.
However, Washington's increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
And where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be a region of (basically) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes the possibility of telling Berlin and Brussels when to let us go.
I suppose Scotland would do well in a liberalised Europe provided it kept its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should follow the example of Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  surprisingly  the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a large majority in 2011 thanks to the opposition stance to the cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the ensuing coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland were to vote for independence now just to adopt austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Early
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is approaching
There's no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are involved.
Experts say that one of the triggers of early puberty may be the obesity epidemic.
The trend toward early puberty is less pronounced in boys.
Former CNN reporter Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be horrified when her daughter starts growing breasts and shameful hair at 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are fairly common among American girls and represent a new standard.
"I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that it's not usually a sign of rapid progress toward full puberty", Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
However, in the last 40 years, there has been little change in the age at which menstruation occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years old, compared with 12.75 years in 1970.
"When breasts start to develop, it takes at least two to three years for the first menstrual period to occur", said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem".
The most reliable test of how puberty will progress is time.
It is debated what actually triggers the onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before age 8, a girl is considered "premature".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops, which can be closely monitored by the pediatrician.
Rapid growth may be a reason for the endocrinologist to perform tests to rule out serious problems, such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent the further consequences: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stunting and curvature in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication and hormone therapy depend on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
There are also psychosocial aspects that are important.
As for the use of drugs, Kaplowitz is cautious, but he recognizes that "suppressing puberty can alleviate the behavioural problems of a girl and her feelings of being different from her peers".
Understandably, there is another big problem: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have their period.
"They're worried she might get pregnant or how she'll handle hygiene", Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock", recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at age 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
But there is no consistent body of evidence yet that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz proposes that the most serious cause is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped lead a study on girls ages 6 to 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations.
Globally, early puberty patterns seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another puzzle: Although boys may experience facial hair at an early age and shame, the trend toward full bloom of early puberty is not as pronounced as it is in girls.
Other physicians attending the American Pediatric Association (AAP) conference added to the complexity of the subject.
Acne and baldness are common even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the actual onset of puberty", said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for instructions on how to talk to their child.
"It may mean having to talk to the child sooner than you expect", advised Kaplowitz.
If you remain calm, your child will likely respond well.
Girls who are developing early need reassurance that even though it is premature, it is a normal part of life.
