Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take the pleasure out of smoking cigarettes.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mice from nicotine addiction for life.
More tests are needed before human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York says the first signs are good.
"We strongly hope that this type of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their addiction to nicotine is so strong that it outpaces all current approaches", said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been engineered to carry the genetic information to create anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then start to produce a steady stream of these antibodies.
The antibodies pursue all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, which were additionally given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
But the unvaccinated mice were calmed down, the researchers said, which is a sign that nicotine had entered their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be given so often to maintain adequate levels of antibodies, they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of the new vaccine should be much lower, because they're turning liver cells into factories to make antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they have the desire to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
However, smokers are much more likely to use it to quit.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not have any pleasure from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and this will help them to get rid of the habit", he said.
