With the growing poverty of the middle class, the pawn shops of Singapore are booming
At a pawn shop in Singapore's Bendemeer mall, Janani Amirthalinga stocks a gold bracelet, ring and earring to pay her daughter's school fees.
"My husband and I just bought a house and I put all my money into it", says Mrs. Amirthalinga.
Although she receives $2,400 a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family's monthly income is not enough, she says.
The demand across Southeast Asia, where household debt is rising, is indeed such that ValueMax, where a woman makes her transaction, has become the third-highest-ranked company on the Singapore Exchange this week.
Stopping jewellery is not only a quick way to borrow cash  1300 SGD in the case of Ms Amirthalinga , but it is also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
The rate of interest charged by the Singapore branch is 17%, just above the rate of 15.4% offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping centre.
However, the advantages of the landlords are that they do not require identification (payment history) or proof of income and can grant loans faster than banks.
And so, with families feeling the pressure of rising living costs and growing household and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to mortgage companies.
After five years of tremendous growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit, supported by loose monetary policies in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to mortgages to cope with their worsening financial situation.
This week, Standard & Poor's ratings agency cited the increasing use of credit by households, primarily due to rising rents, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt per GDP in Asia.
Malaysia tops the list with a share of 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists also feared the high levels of consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely recovered from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed continued weak exports and weaker consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that with rising costs, people from the middle to the low [income] will try to supplement their income wherever they can", said Song Seng Wun, an economist at Malaysia's CIMB Bank.
The historically high gold prices of the past two years have contributed to people temporarily stopping their personal assets and taking the opportunity to exchange their family jewelry for cash.
About 70 percent of the items held in 200 city pawnshops are gold.
People say, "The price of gold looks good, we'll stop Grandma's gold necklace and get it back next month".
The largest pawnshop operator in Thailand, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in the number of customers using its pawnshop in recent months.
