But passengers should not expect changes to happen immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary by airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to demonstrate to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and the equipment storage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on aircraft.
Among the companies that have already submitted plans are Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly", the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the doors of the aircraft are closed.
They can't turn them on until the plane reaches a height of two miles and the captain gives the go-ahead.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again when the aircraft is descending to land and not turn them on until the aircraft is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines with properly protected aircraft against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their equipment during takeoff, landing and takeoff, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been adapted to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Stewards, welcomed the change.
"Once the new rules are safely implemented and we work closely with transport companies on this, it will be a success", Glading said in a statement.
We're tired of looking like the Watchers, to be honest.
