Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said that cell phones continue to be considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigation devices, but we also know from the FCC data that in the air they can cause interference with broadcast towers", Rosenker said.
A sector advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the problem last month suggested the government allow wider use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been under pressure in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Senator Claire McCaskill, a Democrat from Missouri, argue that there is no legitimate security reason for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of such devices is pervasive.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to disruption of navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technical achievement of the day.
The new airlines are far more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed, and approved by the FAA, to be resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi in high altitude travel for several years.
Plans modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to the increased use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
