Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings as to whether these facilities pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passenger Association said he believes the disruption from these facilities is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members stated that there are only fragmentary reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause disruption to aircraft systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off equipment during flight according to instruments in low visibility.
The tourism industry group welcomed these changes and considered that this was a sensible course of action for the traveling public, which makes extensive use of the technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience is not at odds with safety", said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
