Scientists shed more light on how tail movements are linked to a dog's mood
Previous research has shown that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wag their tails mostly to the left.
Now, however, scientists say that other dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences in tail movements.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trent, said: "It is well known that the left and right sides of the brain have different responses to stimuli that trigger positive or negative emotions".
We've been trying to observe the same thing in other species.
He added that, as in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs react to the disproportionate wagging of other dogs' tails, researchers monitored animals watching movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't take long to figure out why their tail sometimes goes one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs the dog movies either in a natural version or in silhouette form to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the tail movement to show it more to the right or left".
When the animals saw the otherwise inconspicuous dog wagging its tail to the right (from the dog's tail-wiggling view), they remained completely calm.
But when she noticed the tail turning mostly to the left (again from the dog's point of view, which was tail-twisting), their heart rate increased, and the animals seemed uncertain.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned by experience what movements they must and must not pay attention to.
He said, "If you meet dogs several times and their tail movements in one direction are repeatedly associated with more friendly behavior and their tail movements to the right produce less friendly behavior, you will react based on that experience".
Researchers say the findings may help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand the emotions of their pets.
Dog behaviorist John Bradshaw, a professor of veterinary medicine at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they see an aggressive dog, and to the right when they see a cheerful dog.
And in another paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs were more likely to recognize a robot dog when it was wagging its tail to the left than to the right, when it was more likely to become uncertain".
The difference, he says, is that in these different studies of animals in movies or dog robots, they didn't interpret themselves as dogs.
He explained that it could help study how dogs react to real dogs.
"Although there is strong evidence that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes in many different mammals, many details still need to be clarified", he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won't take long to understand why their tail sometimes goes one way and sometimes the other.
