Republican obstruction cannot explain the approval of wiretapping of foreign leaders or drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
They can't explain the NSA's collection of data on the private lives of Americans, or the fact that it prosecutes those who expose government misconduct.
He cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, without due process or for restricting public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the findings of a report that says the White House's efforts to silence the media are the most aggressive since the Nixon administration.
And most recently, they can't even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was signed.
I don't know if I expected that.
I should have known at 18 that government power could be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
The elected office obviously has no predictable course and our public conversations will be shaped by the opposition political party and random events like the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above seem to be largely the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
