Muhammad Morsi has taken the oath of office, but his triumphal day is hardly going to end the political turmoil in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Muhammad Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he was inaugurated as the country's first freely elected president, after Hosni Mubarak was ousted 16 months earlier.
When appointed to the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He swore before 18 judges dressed in black robes in a palace overlooking the Nile, reminiscent of an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic", Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
"The Egyptian people today have laid the foundation for a new life of absolute freedom, true democracy and stability", said Morsi, a 60-year-old US-educated engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of sharp attacks by governments for most of the 84 years since its inception as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived in a small convoy of cars shortly after 11 a.m. local time, hundreds of soldiers and police were guarding the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pomp of Mubarak's era, traffic was briefly halted to allow the convoy to pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the southern suburbs.
Morsi's personal prestige, derisively dubbed the uncharismatic spare tire of the Muslim Brotherhood, has grown sharply since his victory and his Friday speech, which was intended to present him not only as the candidate of the Islamists but also of all those who want to end the uprising against authoritarian Mubarak.
"Egypt is now a civil, national, constitutional and modern state", Morsi, dressed in a blue suit and red tie, told the judges in a wood-lined chamber where he was taking the oath.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University to deliver the inaugural address.
While standing guard, he received an official welcome from the military band playing the national anthem.
The military commander, Field Marshal Hussain Tantawi, was brought in.
His arrival was accompanied by the chanting of "Kharmad" and the people are one handed by the hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Cairo University was founded in 1908 as a center of secular education and later became a stronghold of Islamic student movements in the 1970s.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, the birthplace of the revolution that ended Mubarak's authoritarian rule last year, and solemnly promised to reclaim the presidential powers stripped from him by the military council that took over from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take the oath of office in court, rather than parliament, as is customary, he has submitted to the will of the military, suggesting that the power struggle will continue.
Mursi's speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
