Karel Drábek: The Coal Mountain - one of our youngest volcanoes.
Coal Mountain is a prominent hill three kilometres southeast of Bruntal.
Along with several others, it is evidence of volcanic activity in the Low Asenik in recent times (from the geological point of view).
The last eruptions here were at the beginning of the Quaternary.
When viewed from a greater distance, the baroque pilgrimage church of Our Lady of Help, built in 1755-1765, is conspicuously whitewashed on the top of the Coal Hill.
He replaced the original wooden pilgrimage chapel.
The inn next to the church didn't survive.
Shortly after the church was completed, a four-row alley was planted, about 1 km long.
The crossroads on the Coal Hill is the third version, the original was here after 1916, the second from 2001 lasted only until 2004.
At 15 stops there are wooden plaster casts made by the local artistic carver František Nedomlel.
He used different types of wood from the Low Autumn region.
Similarly, the rock beds of the area provide an interesting geological exposure.
Each stop is marked with the name of the sponsor.
The coal mountain is the remnant of a young volcano.
Although radiometric dating varies slightly, the last eruption was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is younger than the Great Red (age 3.3 million years) and older than the Venus volcano (age 0.8 million years).
The volcano was born by explosion.
It spewed a considerable amount of volcanic ash along with fragments of rock from the floor, which burned to a reddish-brown color.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - a layer of porous limestone that is up to 40 feet [13 m] thick today.
The second eruption produced red, reddish-brown, and in places, black tuffs.
Their layer is powerful up to 50 meters and part of it is accessible in the wall of the quarry.
The tuffs are marked by volcanic plumes up to 1 meter in size.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed out of the volcano, which now forms a powerful layer of crustal ash up to 50 m (160 ft).
Volcanoes that alternate between erupting volcanic ash and lava flows are the most common type of volcano.
Because they're actually made up of layers, they're called stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone was gradually eroded.
However, it was only threatened by mining in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here in the years 1953-1962.
The tuffs were added to the concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
Under pressure from experts and the public, the mine was stopped and the unique site was preserved.
The problem is the porosity and poor cohesion of the rocks, which are rapidly weathering, breaking up and moving down the slope.
The hole is disappearing pretty fast.
To complicate matters further, the warm, south-facing slope is ideal for some rare species of plants and animals.
So, the repair is problematic, but over time, it will be necessary to select and maintain a characteristic geological profile.
It's nothing new, similar profiles are maintained at a number of key sites.
The Coal Mountain can be reached by a green tourist sign from Bruntal or Silesian Kočov.
