For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his father fall unconscious over and over again, and drive to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, Cameroon's capital, in 1981.
At first he was treated with only a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to his brain, where it created a hematoma that plagued him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon", says Georges Bwelle.
We'd have to take him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, where he received the kind of treatment that was simply available.
"It's not easy", says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5:00 in the morning, rush to the hospital to be there first, but you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
Since the death of Bwelle's father in 2002, things have not changed much.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 inhabitants in Cameroon.
Just for comparison, the rate in the United States is one doctor for every 413 people.
And even if doctors could visit Cameroon, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the health care spending in this country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty", says Bwelle.
They can't enjoy life because of poverty.
When Bwelle saw his father and many of his countrymen suffer, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he started the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he has helped nearly 32,000 people with his volunteer group.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others rush into vans, attach medical supplies to rooftops, and travel through rough terrain to villages in need.
They don't always have luck.
The vehicles have to push through the river and the mud at one time or another.
But when they arrive, they'll be greeted like true heroes: feasting, singing and dancing and the best accommodations the community has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is a real cause for celebration, and Bwelle  with her broad smile and unbridled energy  is very willing to join in the local cheer.
The next day, the team starts treating hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 patients on each expedition", says Bwelle.
They're coming to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, and they're walking.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide a variety of medical care.
Many are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive free crutches or donated glasses or a birth certificate - a document that the school requires but that many impoverished families simply cannot afford.
Tonight, the team performs a simple operation under local anesthesia.
Surgeries are usually done in a school building, at city hall, or at home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery area to make room for another patient.
With the help of generator lights, operating rooms, and sanitary equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning.
It's exhausting, but the village musicians usually help the team to keep motivation.
"They play drums all night long to keep us up and going", says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team heads back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group - made up of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students - performed 700 free operations last year and they know that their help can mean a lot to the local population.
One man said he'd be able to work again after his kidney was operated on.
"This will change the future of our family", said the man.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
He says that this second job is what funds about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I'm not sure when she actually sleeps", says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers for Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who came from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it's a great practice they wouldn't get at home.
"Dr. Bwell's hands were thoroughly washed and bloodstains removed or we held his tools", says O'Malley.
You'll never experience that as a second-year medical student in America.
Student volunteers usually pay their own way to Cameroon and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaoundé, Bwelle provides them with food, transportation, and education.
"He is a hero, without a doubt", says O'Malley.
He gives his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
Bwelle's constant pursuit is no burden to him.
Helping others to live happier lives, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job", says Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope they see what I'm doing.
To make people laugh, to ease their pain. That's why I do it.
